document.text: Existence and uniqueness of obliquely reflecting Brownian motion
in nonpolyhedral, piecewise smooth cones, with an example of
application to diffusion approximation of bandwidth sharing queues
The paper considers the stochastic differential equation with reflection that defines a
semimartingale Brownian motion in a nonpolyhedral, piecewise smooth cone, with radially
constant direction of reflection on each face. Existence and uniqueness in distribution of
the solution are proved, under suitable assumptions.
The assumptions are shown to be verified by the stochastic differential equation with reflection satisfied by the conjectured limit, under diffusive space-time scaling, of the workload

, thus ensuring that the conjectured limit is uniquely characterized. This is a
key step in proving diffusion approximation for the network.

Input-queued switches are widely used in Internet routing and were studied in Shah and
Wischik (2012) and Kang and Williams (2012). As for bandwidth sharing networks, Kang and
Williams (2012) prove the diffusion approximation for the
case, but the conjecture is not proved for the same reasons as for bandwidth sharing
In fact, few uniqueness results are available for obliquely reflecting diffusions in nonsmooth
or piecewise smooth domains. For a polyhedral domain with constant direction of reflection on
each face, existence and uniqueness of semimartingale ORBM is obtained in Taylor and Williams
(1993) and Dai and Williams (1996). For a piecewise smooth domain with curved faces, Dupuis
and Ishii (1993) prove existence and uniqueness of the solution of a SDER, under a somewhat
restrictive assumption. For a smooth cone with radially constant direction of reflection Kwon
and Williams (1991) prove existence and uniqueness of the solution to the submartingale problem
corresponding to ORBM. More recently Costantini and Kurtz (2021) have proposed a different
approach that allows to obtain existence and uniqueness of the solution to a SDER in a smooth
cone with non radially constant direction of reflection and in a curved domain with one singular
The results of Costantini and Kurtz (2021) are used in Costantini and Kurtz (2022)
The uniqueness result of Costantini and Kurtz (2021) is based on a reverse ergodic theorem
for inhomogeneous killed Markov chains. This work shows that the same theorem can be applied
also to obtain uniqueness of semimartingale ORBM in a piecewise smooth cone with curved
faces (Sections 2 and 3.) For simplicity it is assumed that the direction of reflection on each face
is radially constant, but the result should hold without this restriction. In order to apply the
ergodic theorem of Costantini and Kurtz (2021), essentially one needs: To know uniqueness until
the first time the vertex is hit; To satisfy a certain geometric condition at the vertex; To have one
or, in some cases, two certain auxiliary functions. In Costantini and Kurtz (2021) these auxiliary
functions are constructed from the auxiliary functions of Kwon and Williams (1991) exploiting
the geometric condition at the vertex. For a piecewise smooth cone these auxilary functions have
to be found directly in each instance. This is the main difference in the assumptions between
Costantini and Kurtz (2021) and the present paper. Many of the arguments of Costantini and
Kurtz (2021) can be modified to work in the present context. As in Costantini and Kurtz (2021),
existence of a semimartingale, strong Markov ORBM is proved preliminarly.

In general, diffusion processes with boundary conditions can be characterized also as atural
solutions of constrained martingale problems. Characterizing the process as the natural solution
of a constrained martingale problem allows to verify tightness in a much simpler way, whenever
an approximation or convergence argument is needed. The reader is referred to Kurtz (1990),
Kurtz (1991)), Costantini and Kurtz (2015) and Costantini and Kurtz (2019) for a complete
treatment of constrained martingale problems. In these works the state space is compact, but
the definitions extend to a noncompact state space without any modification and most of the
results hold in a non compact state space as well.
